90s' most popular genre, action, channeled anxieties about global threats such as AIDS and foreign terrorist attacks into escapist entertainment movies. Horror films and thrillers were on the rise, but family-friendly pictures and feel-good romances netted big audiences too. Meanwhile, independent films captured hearts, engaged minds, and invaded Hollywood: by decade's end every studio boasted its own "art film" affiliate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxPlots, themes, etc. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aCapino, José B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapino, José.1 aFlinn, Caryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlinn, Caryl.1 aGabbard, Krin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, Krin.1 aHolmlund, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmlund, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolmlund, Chris.1 aKleinhans, Chuck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKleinhans, Chuck.1 aMizejewski, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMizejewski, Linda.1 aShary, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShary, Timothy.1 aVillarejo, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVillarejo, Amy.1 aWaldman, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaldman, Diane.1 aWhite-Stanley, Debra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite-Stanley, Debra.1 aWillis, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/